WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:06.640
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:06.640 --> 00:00:11.470
&gt;&gt; Steven Levingston: Eric Weiner
is a wanderer, a searcher for God,

00:00:11.470 --> 00:00:13.770
for genius, for happiness.

00:00:13.770 --> 00:00:17.920
Fortunately for us he takes
us on his journeys and we get

00:00:17.920 --> 00:00:22.690
to see his humor, his
curiosity, his deep intelligence.

00:00:22.690 --> 00:00:27.570
In his book, Man Seeks God, he went
in search of the divine traveling

00:00:27.570 --> 00:00:32.810
to Nepal to try Buddhism, to the
Bronx to mix with the Franciscans,

00:00:32.810 --> 00:00:35.230
to China to take in the Daoists,

00:00:35.230 --> 00:00:39.350
and to Israel to plunge
into the Kabbalah.

00:00:39.350 --> 00:00:43.140 position:56%
In his search for happiness, Weiner,
again traveled far and wide seeking

00:00:43.140 --> 00:00:46.570
to discover the happiest
place on the planet.

00:00:46.570 --> 00:00:48.840
Perhaps, not surprisingly, he found

00:00:48.840 --> 00:00:52.530
that happiness is not a
place but a state of mind.

00:00:52.530 --> 00:00:57.280
And the things that people normally
think bring us happiness do not.

00:00:57.280 --> 00:01:01.570 position:56%
If money were the key, why do people
living in humble circumstances

00:01:01.570 --> 00:01:05.070
in Latin America say
that they're very happy.

00:01:05.070 --> 00:01:10.540
In his latest book, The Geography
of Genius, Weiner sets off

00:01:10.540 --> 00:01:14.940
on another worldly quest to
find the wellspring of genius.

00:01:14.940 --> 00:01:16.670
And he comes to the realization

00:01:16.670 --> 00:01:21.250
that genius is not necessarily what
we have always imagined it to be.

00:01:21.250 --> 00:01:24.150
Of course, we have our
solitary tortured geniuses,

00:01:24.150 --> 00:01:27.390
van Gogh, Mozart, da Vinci.

00:01:27.390 --> 00:01:31.190
But Weiner looks beyond the
individual to the times and places

00:01:31.190 --> 00:01:34.420
that gave rise to --
gave birth to genius.

00:01:34.420 --> 00:01:38.090
And he discovers that genius
often arose after a period

00:01:38.090 --> 00:01:41.970 position:56%
of hardship, chaos, and uncertainty.

00:01:41.970 --> 00:01:46.730
In many cases a mixing of different
cultures was a contributing factor.

00:01:47.910 --> 00:01:51.060
Before he combed the
world as an author,

00:01:51.060 --> 00:01:54.000
Weiner was foreign
correspondent for NPR reporting

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:57.430
for more than 30 countries.

00:01:57.430 --> 00:02:02.510
Now, please join me in
welcoming Eric Weiner.

00:02:02.510 --> 00:02:13.480
[ Applause ]

00:02:13.480 --> 00:02:14.780
&gt;&gt; Eric Weiner: Wow.

00:02:14.780 --> 00:02:18.780
I think I may have to add a chapter
to my book about the geography

00:02:18.780 --> 00:02:22.400
of genius include this room.

00:02:22.400 --> 00:02:27.170
Because I sense a lot
of genius out there.

00:02:27.170 --> 00:02:29.440
Steve, thank you for
that great introduction.

00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:33.130
I think you did neatly
sort of sum up what I do.

00:02:33.130 --> 00:02:38.790
Because it's not always easy to
explain to people what I do when,

00:02:38.790 --> 00:02:43.920
you know, you have to fill out
the forms and put occupation,

00:02:43.920 --> 00:02:47.740
I usually write philosophical
traveler.

00:02:47.740 --> 00:02:49.880
This is -- confuses
people at the IRS

00:02:49.880 --> 00:02:53.300
and makes you subject
to audits, you know.

00:02:53.300 --> 00:02:56.570
But that really is what
I'm doing is I'm looking

00:02:56.570 --> 00:03:02.110
for the intersection
of place and idea.

00:03:02.110 --> 00:03:05.300
And I've always been a traveler

00:03:05.300 --> 00:03:07.420
and I've always done my
best thinking on the road.

00:03:07.420 --> 00:03:12.140
Ever since I was five years old and
I ran away from home, true story,

00:03:12.140 --> 00:03:14.280
and I got a good mile
and-a-half away from home

00:03:14.280 --> 00:03:16.790
and would have made it to
wherever it was I was trying to get

00:03:16.790 --> 00:03:20.110
to had Baltimore County
Police not decided to,

00:03:20.110 --> 00:03:24.240
I thought a bit impetuously,
intervene with my little adventure.

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:26.590
But ever since I've been
wandering and as Steve said looking

00:03:26.590 --> 00:03:32.000
at big ideas, like happiness, like
spirituality and now like genius,

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:36.810
not just any ideas, ideas where
I feel that the role of place

00:03:36.810 --> 00:03:42.530
or geography in the biggest sense
of the word is often overlooked.

00:03:42.530 --> 00:03:47.200
And I do think that is the case
with genius because there are a lot

00:03:47.200 --> 00:03:53.840
of theories, slash,
myths surrounding genius.

00:03:53.840 --> 00:03:55.840
It's a big word; right?

00:03:55.840 --> 00:03:59.360
It comes to us like so
many words from Latin.

00:03:59.360 --> 00:04:02.870
But the Latin notion of genius was

00:04:02.870 --> 00:04:05.080
that it was not something
you achieved;

00:04:05.080 --> 00:04:07.500
it was something that
accompanied you.

00:04:07.500 --> 00:04:11.960
A sort of presiding spirit or
deity that followed you around.

00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:13.320
You had your genius take --

00:04:13.320 --> 00:04:17.590
you know, sort of travel
with you everywhere.

00:04:17.590 --> 00:04:21.700
And today it means
lots of things; right?

00:04:21.700 --> 00:04:24.330
It might mean someone
with a really high IQ

00:04:24.330 --> 00:04:27.350
or someone who's a
really know-it-all.

00:04:27.350 --> 00:04:29.620
That's not the definition
I'm working with.

00:04:29.620 --> 00:04:33.180
I believe that genius
is not a know-it-all.

00:04:33.180 --> 00:04:36.260
A genius is a see-it-all,
someone who sees connections.

00:04:36.260 --> 00:04:38.560
Someone who is creative really.

00:04:38.560 --> 00:04:40.730
Creative genius.

00:04:40.730 --> 00:04:45.840
But where do these
creative geniuses come from?

00:04:45.840 --> 00:04:47.170
Well, myth No.

00:04:47.170 --> 00:04:49.200
1, and I use the term myth in sort

00:04:49.200 --> 00:04:51.240
of the Joseph Campbell
sense is it's something

00:04:51.240 --> 00:04:53.480
that can be very empowering
and perhaps partially true

00:04:53.480 --> 00:04:55.220
but not 100 percent true.

00:04:55.220 --> 00:04:58.480
Myth No. 1 is that
geniuses are born.

00:04:58.480 --> 00:05:01.540
They just pop out of the
womb fully brilliant.

00:05:01.540 --> 00:05:05.180
Think of Mozart as sort of the
poster child for this theory.

00:05:05.180 --> 00:05:09.670
You know, playing the violin at age
three and composing at age eight,

00:05:09.670 --> 00:05:13.420
it must have been that he
was born that way; right?

00:05:13.420 --> 00:05:17.450
Ignoring the fact that his
father Leopold Mozart was one

00:05:17.450 --> 00:05:21.300
of premier violin instructors
and musicians of the time

00:05:21.300 --> 00:05:23.160
and that he was growing
up in a very musical era

00:05:23.160 --> 00:05:25.620
in a very musical city of Salzburg.

00:05:25.620 --> 00:05:31.230
So I don't believe that
genetics accounts for as much

00:05:31.230 --> 00:05:32.970
as we think of the genius puzzle.

00:05:32.970 --> 00:05:38.200
And the second myth, again in
quotes, is that geniuses are made

00:05:38.200 --> 00:05:40.670
through hard work; right?

00:05:40.670 --> 00:05:43.760
It's the 10,000 hour theory which
you may be familiar with, you know.

00:05:43.760 --> 00:05:47.480
Put in at least 10,000 hours of
work over ten years and you have

00:05:47.480 --> 00:05:52.350
at least a chance of achieving
excellence if not genius.

00:05:52.350 --> 00:05:56.900
Well, I know a lot of hard
working people in North Korea

00:05:56.900 --> 00:06:02.190
with good genes who
aren't achieving genius.

00:06:02.190 --> 00:06:06.880
And there have been plenty of
hard working women in ages past

00:06:06.880 --> 00:06:09.620
who did not achieve
the status of genius

00:06:09.620 --> 00:06:13.220
because they weren't recognized and
they weren't given the opportunity.

00:06:13.220 --> 00:06:17.120
I don't think genetics and
hard work alone explains it.

00:06:17.120 --> 00:06:18.880
In fact, I began to
think about this.

00:06:18.880 --> 00:06:21.910
So I thought, well, what
if geniuses are not born,

00:06:21.910 --> 00:06:25.420
what if they're not made,
what if they're grown.

00:06:25.420 --> 00:06:27.510
What if it's actually in the soil.

00:06:27.510 --> 00:06:30.090
Think about, you know,
growing an apple tree; right?

00:06:30.090 --> 00:06:32.360
You need to have the
seed, good quality seed.

00:06:32.360 --> 00:06:35.700
You need to put in some
hard work planting it.

00:06:35.700 --> 00:06:37.050
That's the work part.

00:06:37.050 --> 00:06:39.360
But you need to have the right soil

00:06:39.360 --> 00:06:43.440
or you're not going
to have an apple tree.

00:06:43.440 --> 00:06:47.730 position:56%
So, in fact, as I investigated this,
if you look at a map of the world

00:06:47.730 --> 00:06:51.700
over the course of history and
you were to plot the appearance

00:06:51.700 --> 00:06:54.830
of geniuses, of the
Beethovens and the Einsteins

00:06:54.830 --> 00:06:57.870
and others throughout
history, you know,

00:06:57.870 --> 00:07:02.510 position:56%
you wouldn't find them appearing
randomly, you know, one in Belgrade,

00:07:02.510 --> 00:07:07.560
one in Vienna, one in Alexandria,
two in Alexandria, I don't know.

00:07:07.560 --> 00:07:13.010
But you don't -- what you find is
that they are in these groupings.

00:07:13.010 --> 00:07:16.080
Genius clusters I call them; right?

00:07:16.080 --> 00:07:21.660
Certain places at certain
times have just been very good

00:07:21.660 --> 00:07:25.410
at producing brilliant
minds and good ideas.

00:07:25.410 --> 00:07:28.880
And the question is why.

00:07:28.880 --> 00:07:33.280
What was in the water back then
and for selfish reasons we want

00:07:33.280 --> 00:07:36.560
to know can we bottle it; right?

00:07:36.560 --> 00:07:39.940
I'm interested in the history
but it's sort of applied history.

00:07:39.940 --> 00:07:43.780
What are the lessons for us today.

00:07:43.780 --> 00:07:50.510
So I came up with a list of
seven golden ages ranging

00:07:50.510 --> 00:07:53.450
from ancient Athens
to Silicon Valley.

00:07:53.450 --> 00:07:56.630
Some of them were pretty well known
to most of my readers, I think,

00:07:56.630 --> 00:08:00.110
such as Athens during
the Classical period,

00:08:00.110 --> 00:08:03.040
Florence during the Renaissance.

00:08:03.040 --> 00:08:07.160
Others were maybe not as
well known such as Edinburgh

00:08:07.160 --> 00:08:11.900
in the 18th century in the time of
the -- the Scottish Enlightenment.

00:08:11.900 --> 00:08:15.460
Or Vienna which had a rare double
dip of genius which I'll talk

00:08:15.460 --> 00:08:18.220
about both in Mozart and
Beethoven's time and then

00:08:18.220 --> 00:08:20.700
in Freud's time around 1900.

00:08:20.700 --> 00:08:22.890
And some of the places
I chose are really

00:08:22.890 --> 00:08:27.640
for most readers a terra
incognita I would say.

00:08:27.640 --> 00:08:32.370
Hangzhou china in the 13th century,
an amazing, amazing genius cluster

00:08:32.370 --> 00:08:35.220
that we don't, in the West
at least, know much about.

00:08:35.220 --> 00:08:36.740
Or Calcutta.

00:08:36.740 --> 00:08:42.060
Yes, Calcutta in India in the
late 19th, early 20th century home

00:08:42.060 --> 00:08:46.720 position:56%
to the Bengal Renaissance where more
books were published than any city

00:08:46.720 --> 00:08:51.620
in the world except for London and
produced the first non-Westerner

00:08:51.620 --> 00:08:55.740
to win the Nobel Prize for
literature, Rabindranath Tagore.

00:08:55.740 --> 00:08:59.130
And then I bring the book home to
Silicon Valley because I wanted

00:08:59.130 --> 00:09:01.650
to bring it home, and
I wanted to bring it

00:09:01.650 --> 00:09:04.940
to a current place of genius.

00:09:04.940 --> 00:09:09.620
So word about what the academics
would call methodology and what I

00:09:09.620 --> 00:09:12.160
like to call how I do stuff.

00:09:12.160 --> 00:09:18.250
I do -- here's my sort
of philosophy of travel.

00:09:18.250 --> 00:09:23.780
Read about a place before you go
there but don't read too much.

00:09:23.780 --> 00:09:27.190
I would read lots of histories
before I would go somewhere.

00:09:27.190 --> 00:09:29.440
But I didn't want to read other
contemporary authors accounts

00:09:29.440 --> 00:09:34.750
because I wanted to have
a fresh take on places.

00:09:34.750 --> 00:09:36.070
I also am a loiterer.

00:09:36.070 --> 00:09:37.730
I will go some place
and spend more time

00:09:37.730 --> 00:09:40.360
than I think I need to spend there.

00:09:40.360 --> 00:09:43.170
Now the challenge for me in this
book was writing about the past.

00:09:43.170 --> 00:09:44.470
In my previous books I've written

00:09:44.470 --> 00:09:48.500
about contemporary India
or Bhutan or Iceland.

00:09:48.500 --> 00:09:52.000
The past, it's been said,
is a foreign country.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.360
They do things differently there.

00:09:54.360 --> 00:09:55.660
And it's true.

00:09:55.660 --> 00:09:58.320
So the challenge was to make
these places come alive.

00:09:58.320 --> 00:10:01.720
I suppose I could have written
this entire book without leaving,

00:10:01.720 --> 00:10:04.040
say the Library of Congress.

00:10:04.040 --> 00:10:05.340
But that's not the way I roll.

00:10:05.340 --> 00:10:08.430
I really -- I feel because people
have asked me that question, like,

00:10:08.430 --> 00:10:10.830
well, do you really
think you need to go

00:10:10.830 --> 00:10:12.390
to Athens and the answer is yes.

00:10:12.390 --> 00:10:16.670
I think to walk in the footsteps
of Socrates or Plato or Aristotle

00:10:16.670 --> 00:10:23.370
and to experience the place they
experienced is vitally important.

00:10:23.370 --> 00:10:27.690
So I want to give you a
quick world tour of some

00:10:27.690 --> 00:10:31.720
of the places I visited,
what I found,

00:10:31.720 --> 00:10:37.090
and then open it up to questions.

00:10:37.090 --> 00:10:39.640
So I start in Athens.

00:10:39.640 --> 00:10:45.700
And Athens is a mystery; okay.

00:10:45.700 --> 00:10:52.660
It's a mystery because of all the
places to produce so much genius

00:10:52.660 --> 00:10:58.370
in such a short period of time, you
wouldn't necessarily choose Athens

00:10:58.370 --> 00:11:01.900
because remember there
were hundreds and hundreds

00:11:01.900 --> 00:11:03.560
of these Greek city states.

00:11:03.560 --> 00:11:08.520
Hundreds of Greeces, you
know, little microcultures.

00:11:08.520 --> 00:11:13.770
And Athens did not
have the most going

00:11:13.770 --> 00:11:18.200
for it compared to
these other places.

00:11:18.200 --> 00:11:24.080
So I'm just going to read a
little section to give you a sense

00:11:24.080 --> 00:11:30.390
of my task, what I was up to, and
what I found out about Athens.

00:11:30.390 --> 00:11:33.180
As I said "the past
is a foreign country;

00:11:33.180 --> 00:11:35.130
they do things differently there.

00:11:35.130 --> 00:11:36.720
Yes, they do.

00:11:36.720 --> 00:11:39.280
And unfortunately this
particular foreign country known

00:11:39.280 --> 00:11:43.460
as ancient Greece has
extremely tight border controls.

00:11:43.460 --> 00:11:47.010
It doesn't take kindly to
interlopers such as me.

00:11:47.010 --> 00:11:49.250
Yet, if I'm going to solve
the Athenian mystery,

00:11:49.250 --> 00:11:52.250
the past is exactly
where I need to be.

00:11:52.250 --> 00:11:54.300
What to do?

00:11:54.300 --> 00:11:58.900
Squint. That was the
advice of a friend back home

00:11:58.900 --> 00:12:01.490
when I had mentioned my
plans to visit Athens.

00:12:01.490 --> 00:12:05.310
I laughed it off but now I realize
it's actually a smart tactic.

00:12:05.310 --> 00:12:07.980
Sometimes we can see more
by narrowing our field

00:12:07.980 --> 00:12:10.030
of view than by expanding it.

00:12:10.030 --> 00:12:14.850
The zoom lens reveals as much as
the wide angle and sometimes more.

00:12:14.850 --> 00:12:18.460
Don't squint too much,
Aristotle warns."

00:12:18.460 --> 00:12:22.310
I should say that Aristotle is
the name of my guide in Athens.

00:12:22.310 --> 00:12:24.250
Talk about a wonderful
piece of serendipity.

00:12:24.250 --> 00:12:27.590
It's kind of burden, though,
when your name is Aristotle.

00:12:27.590 --> 00:12:29.290
And I really thought at
first, well, this is great.

00:12:29.290 --> 00:12:30.830
And he's like, you
know, it's not so great.

00:12:30.830 --> 00:12:33.770
People assume great
wisdom on his part.

00:12:33.770 --> 00:12:37.670
And he's plenty smart but, you
know, you don't want that name.

00:12:37.670 --> 00:12:43.770
"If I could time travel, he
says, to Athens circa 450 BC,

00:12:43.770 --> 00:12:46.060
I'd probably be disappointed.

00:12:46.060 --> 00:12:49.890 position:56%
The great Athens, the cradle of
Western civilization, the birthplace

00:12:49.890 --> 00:12:54.930
of science, philosophy, and so
much else we hold dear was a dump.

00:12:54.930 --> 00:12:56.570
The streets were narrow and dirty.

00:12:56.570 --> 00:13:00.940
The houses constructed of wood
and sun dried clay were so flimsy

00:13:00.940 --> 00:13:03.980
that robbers gained
entry by simply digging.

00:13:03.980 --> 00:13:07.460
In fact, the ancient Greek word
for robber means literally one

00:13:07.460 --> 00:13:09.120
who tunnels through walls.

00:13:09.120 --> 00:13:12.200
As a time traveler I would
definitely notice the noise,

00:13:12.200 --> 00:13:15.140
vendors hawking their wares
at the Agora, a flute,

00:13:15.140 --> 00:13:17.460
a lute rather screeching off key.

00:13:17.460 --> 00:13:22.350
But what would grab my attention
and not let go is the stench.

00:13:22.350 --> 00:13:25.150
People relieved themselves in
the courtyard of their own home

00:13:25.150 --> 00:13:27.510
or even right in the streets
where the mess would sit

00:13:27.510 --> 00:13:29.920
until a slave sluiced it away.

00:13:29.920 --> 00:13:33.640
Conditions were such that as
historian Jacob Burckhardt put it,

00:13:33.640 --> 00:13:36.200
no sensible and peaceful person

00:13:36.200 --> 00:13:38.600
of our day would want
to live under that."

00:13:38.600 --> 00:13:43.140
And he wrote those words by
the way in the 19th century.

00:13:43.140 --> 00:13:47.660
So this is one of the great myths
of these places of genius is

00:13:47.660 --> 00:13:52.330
that they're paradise, that
they're really nice places.

00:13:52.330 --> 00:13:53.670
They're not.

00:13:53.670 --> 00:13:55.720
They're difficult places.

00:13:55.720 --> 00:13:59.100
I really believe that one
of the keys to creativity is

00:13:59.100 --> 00:14:01.020
that we need constraints.

00:14:01.020 --> 00:14:03.650
We need something to push against.

00:14:03.650 --> 00:14:05.500
And paradise if it does exist

00:14:05.500 --> 00:14:09.300 position:56%
and I hope it does is probably the
least creative place in the universe

00:14:09.300 --> 00:14:12.450
because you don't have that
need to create something.

00:14:12.450 --> 00:14:16.440
You don't have that
something to push against.

00:14:16.440 --> 00:14:19.110
You know, there was one
very interesting study done

00:14:19.110 --> 00:14:22.100
by a psychologist where
he gave two groups

00:14:22.100 --> 00:14:26.280
of people an assignment
to build a collage.

00:14:26.280 --> 00:14:30.290
But one group was given a very
limited number of materials

00:14:30.290 --> 00:14:33.570 position:56%
and limited number of options of how
they can work with these materials.

00:14:33.570 --> 00:14:34.870
And the other was given
a whole bunch

00:14:34.870 --> 00:14:37.280
of material and lots of options.

00:14:37.280 --> 00:14:39.950
And it was that first group
with the greater constraints

00:14:39.950 --> 00:14:44.870
who produced the more creative,
as judged by a panel, collages.

00:14:44.870 --> 00:14:46.570
We need something to push against.

00:14:46.570 --> 00:14:50.300
And we need that sort of messiness,
I don't know about the stench,

00:14:50.300 --> 00:14:54.610
but the messiness that you had
in Athens because creativity

00:14:54.610 --> 00:14:57.470
and creative genius
is not a neat process.

00:14:57.470 --> 00:15:00.580
There is a messiness to it

00:15:00.580 --> 00:15:02.790
and that's why you
often see relationship

00:15:02.790 --> 00:15:04.970
between chaos and creativity.

00:15:04.970 --> 00:15:07.770
If you think about it, if you're
going from the old way of thinking

00:15:07.770 --> 00:15:10.460
to the new way of thinking,
you need to pass

00:15:10.460 --> 00:15:11.990
through an intermediate stage.

00:15:11.990 --> 00:15:15.560
That intermediate stage is chaos.

00:15:15.560 --> 00:15:18.440
A neuroscientist named Walter
Freeman studied the brains

00:15:18.440 --> 00:15:19.840
of rabbits.

00:15:19.840 --> 00:15:21.610
No rabbits were harmed
in these experiments.

00:15:21.610 --> 00:15:24.300 position:56%
I just want you to know because I
always feel uncomfortable with that.

00:15:24.300 --> 00:15:27.790
But he hooked up their
little rabbit brains to EEGs

00:15:27.790 --> 00:15:29.380
and he introduced them to odors.

00:15:29.380 --> 00:15:31.090
And some odors they
were quite familiar with

00:15:31.090 --> 00:15:33.810
and other odors they
were new to them.

00:15:33.810 --> 00:15:38.010 position:56%
Well, when they saw a familiar
odor, the EEG had a regular readout.

00:15:38.010 --> 00:15:41.130
When they were introduced
to an unfamiliar odor,

00:15:41.130 --> 00:15:45.060
they saw a very chaotic
state on the EEG.

00:15:45.060 --> 00:15:48.020
And Freeman called that very
interestingly the I don't

00:15:48.020 --> 00:15:49.540
know state.

00:15:49.540 --> 00:15:54.580
And that I don't know state is
essential for creative genius

00:15:54.580 --> 00:16:00.680
and it's essential that these
places nurture it, cultivate it.

00:16:00.680 --> 00:16:02.560
One thing I should add about
all these places they have

00:16:02.560 --> 00:16:04.460
in common is they're
almost all cities.

00:16:04.460 --> 00:16:09.170
If it takes a village to raise a
child as the African proverb goes,

00:16:09.170 --> 00:16:11.720
it takes a city to make a genius.

00:16:11.720 --> 00:16:15.670
I won't say to raise a genius
but to cultivate a genius.

00:16:15.670 --> 00:16:19.730
Because cities provide
the opportunities;

00:16:19.730 --> 00:16:22.730
cities provide the audience
which is hugely important.

00:16:22.730 --> 00:16:28.540
And a city like Athens
had the one single trait

00:16:28.540 --> 00:16:31.090
that psychologists have identified
as the most important trait

00:16:31.090 --> 00:16:35.090
for creative people and I
would argue for creative places

00:16:35.090 --> 00:16:38.770
and that is this, openness
to experience.

00:16:38.770 --> 00:16:40.410
Openness to experience.

00:16:40.410 --> 00:16:41.710
And the manifestation of that

00:16:41.710 --> 00:16:44.840
in ancient Athens was
the Port of Piraeus.

00:16:44.840 --> 00:16:47.600
And they went out and
they sailed and here's one

00:16:47.600 --> 00:16:50.070
of the dirty little secrets
about the ancient Greeks.

00:16:50.070 --> 00:16:51.370
They mooched.

00:16:51.370 --> 00:16:52.830
They were tremendous moochers.

00:16:52.830 --> 00:16:57.200
They borrowed ideas
statuary from the Egyptians

00:16:57.200 --> 00:16:59.490
and mathematics from elsewhere.

00:16:59.490 --> 00:17:03.710 position:56%
As Plato said though what the Greeks
borrow, very nice way of putting it,

00:17:03.710 --> 00:17:05.820
or steal from foreigners
they perfect.

00:17:05.820 --> 00:17:08.370
And there's nothing wrong
with that, you know.

00:17:08.370 --> 00:17:11.150
As the historian Will
Durant said something

00:17:11.150 --> 00:17:14.640
that at first I found disturbing
and later I've come to embrace.

00:17:14.640 --> 00:17:17.640
He said, nothing is
new but the arranging.

00:17:17.640 --> 00:17:19.060
Nothing is new but the arranging.

00:17:19.060 --> 00:17:21.950
At first as a writer,
I thought, oh, shoot.

00:17:21.950 --> 00:17:23.620
Well, I've got nothing new to say.

00:17:23.620 --> 00:17:27.620
But then I realized there's
great beauty in the arranging,

00:17:27.620 --> 00:17:28.920
you know, and the rearranging.

00:17:28.920 --> 00:17:34.530
You can probably find every word
that I have in this book somewhere

00:17:34.530 --> 00:17:37.920
out there in other books scattered
around the world but not arranged

00:17:37.920 --> 00:17:40.580
in the particular way
I've arranged them.

00:17:40.580 --> 00:17:44.160
So genius is about the art of
stealing and borrowing as well.

00:17:44.160 --> 00:17:47.780
And just -- this is going to be a
quick whirlwind tour but let's talk

00:17:47.780 --> 00:17:51.150
about another well known place
which is Florence; right?

00:17:51.150 --> 00:17:55.320 position:56%
A couple interesting things about
Florence in the Italian Renaissance.

00:17:55.320 --> 00:17:58.710
One is that it was born
out of catastrophe.

00:17:58.710 --> 00:18:04.130 position:56%
That the Italian Renaissance which
started in Florence started not more

00:18:04.130 --> 00:18:07.960 position:56%
than a few decades after the
outbreak of the bubonic plague known

00:18:07.960 --> 00:18:11.400
as the black death which was
horrible, which was terrible,

00:18:11.400 --> 00:18:14.320
which should not be
wished on any society.

00:18:14.320 --> 00:18:21.180 position:56%
But it had this effect of shaking up
the culture of making it less rigid.

00:18:21.180 --> 00:18:23.650
And some historians believe,
and I subscribe to this,

00:18:23.650 --> 00:18:27.380
that it was that shaking
up that ultimately led

00:18:27.380 --> 00:18:30.190
to the flourishing known
as the Renaissance.

00:18:30.190 --> 00:18:31.810
And the other interesting thing

00:18:31.810 --> 00:18:35.620
about the Italian Renaissance is
the role that money played in it.

00:18:35.620 --> 00:18:38.750
Now we have this very romantic
notion of this starving artist.

00:18:38.750 --> 00:18:40.050
Forget it.

00:18:40.050 --> 00:18:42.290
The starving artist doesn't
produce anything except his own --

00:18:42.290 --> 00:18:43.590
or her own misery.

00:18:43.590 --> 00:18:45.760
They're always worried
about their next meal.

00:18:45.760 --> 00:18:48.040 position:56%
So some degree of money is required.

00:18:48.040 --> 00:18:53.410
And this is where patronage
comes into play.

00:18:53.410 --> 00:18:58.430 position:56%
And it took the form of one
particular family, the Medici who --

00:18:58.430 --> 00:19:01.060
it's not enough just
to throw money around.

00:19:01.060 --> 00:19:04.350
You have to know what you're doing
and they knew what they were doing.

00:19:04.350 --> 00:19:09.500
And there's a great story about
Lorenzo Medici who was known

00:19:09.500 --> 00:19:11.300
as Lorenzo the Magnificent.

00:19:11.300 --> 00:19:14.150
I think it said it
on his business card.

00:19:14.150 --> 00:19:16.740
I think that's just how he went by.

00:19:16.740 --> 00:19:24.380
And one day he is -- he's walking
outside the sort of palace grounds

00:19:24.380 --> 00:19:27.270
in the Medici gardens and he
sees this young stone cutter

00:19:27.270 --> 00:19:30.800
who can't be more than 14
years old working on a sort

00:19:30.800 --> 00:19:34.940
of rudimentary statute
of a fawn, a Roman deity.

00:19:34.940 --> 00:19:37.850
And Lorenzo, who's getting
up there in age by now,

00:19:37.850 --> 00:19:40.030
says well that's pretty good, kid.

00:19:40.030 --> 00:19:44.190
But, you know, it's an older fawn
and it's teeth though are new.

00:19:44.190 --> 00:19:47.070
When you're an older man like
me your teeth don't look so new.

00:19:47.070 --> 00:19:49.240
And he walked away.

00:19:49.240 --> 00:19:51.090 position:56%
Comes back the next day Lorenzo does

00:19:51.090 --> 00:19:54.230
and notices the kid has
perfected the teeth and put

00:19:54.230 --> 00:19:58.230
in a little tooth decay and
really created something special.

00:19:58.230 --> 00:20:00.140
And -- and --

00:20:00.140 --> 00:20:02.820
Lorenzo is sort of on
this spot, takes a chance.

00:20:02.820 --> 00:20:06.780
Makes an investment in that kid
and says you come live with me,

00:20:06.780 --> 00:20:11.280
basically live with me, become
a part of my family essentially.

00:20:11.280 --> 00:20:15.780
I'm going to give you the best
access to teachers and to materials

00:20:15.780 --> 00:20:18.250
and the highest challenges.

00:20:18.250 --> 00:20:21.070
And it was a very wise investment
because today that kid goes

00:20:21.070 --> 00:20:24.640
by just one name usually,
Michelangelo.

00:20:24.640 --> 00:20:28.100
Now we think of Michelangelo
as the genius, he's well known.

00:20:28.100 --> 00:20:31.240
Lorenzo the Magnificent less so.

00:20:31.240 --> 00:20:32.900
But you can argue that
without Lorenzo

00:20:32.900 --> 00:20:36.150
and his patronage there would be
no Michelangelo and you can argue

00:20:36.150 --> 00:20:37.970
that the real genius was Lorenzo.

00:20:37.970 --> 00:20:41.880
You could also argue as I would
that the real genius was the city

00:20:41.880 --> 00:20:45.150
of Florence and their appreciation

00:20:45.150 --> 00:20:48.540
and their willingness
to make bets like that.

00:20:48.540 --> 00:20:53.870
Another Michelangelo story
is Pope Julius II was looking

00:20:53.870 --> 00:20:58.500
to have some ceiling work
done on the Sistine Chapel.

00:20:58.500 --> 00:21:02.140
So he sends out bids to
contractors essentially.

00:21:02.140 --> 00:21:06.470
But he chose Michelangelo which was
-- now we look back and say, well,

00:21:06.470 --> 00:21:07.770
that's such an obvious choice.

00:21:07.770 --> 00:21:09.640
It wasn't at the time, you know.

00:21:09.640 --> 00:21:14.770
Michelangelo was mainly
a statute maker.

00:21:14.770 --> 00:21:16.290
He was a, you know,
a sculptor rather.

00:21:16.290 --> 00:21:20.640
He was not -- he was not
so much of a painter.

00:21:20.640 --> 00:21:24.090
But that, I think, is
something essential

00:21:24.090 --> 00:21:25.390
and something we've lost a bit on.

00:21:25.390 --> 00:21:28.380
That's taking, making a big bet

00:21:28.380 --> 00:21:31.210
on someone whose not the
exact fit for the job.

00:21:31.210 --> 00:21:35.080
Think of how many jobs today, like,
we look to hire someone who's done

00:21:35.080 --> 00:21:37.250
that exact same job previously.

00:21:37.250 --> 00:21:41.260
But the Pope who was a Medici
from the family took a bet

00:21:41.260 --> 00:21:46.260
on Michelangelo and it
paid off tremendously.

00:21:46.260 --> 00:21:50.450
Other places.

00:21:50.450 --> 00:21:52.350
Hung jo China.

00:21:52.350 --> 00:21:56.790
So in the 13th century, you
know, Europe is pretty backward.

00:21:56.790 --> 00:21:59.590
You know, they're picking fleas out
of each other's hair and wondering

00:21:59.590 --> 00:22:01.950
when the Dark Ages are
ever, ever going to end.

00:22:01.950 --> 00:22:03.250
This is just going on too long.

00:22:03.250 --> 00:22:06.050
But at the time Hangzhou
is a flourishing city

00:22:06.050 --> 00:22:10.740
of a million people,
you know, or more.

00:22:10.740 --> 00:22:13.310
And it is just taking off.

00:22:13.310 --> 00:22:15.910
And they're sailing ships
that are unlike anything

00:22:15.910 --> 00:22:17.360
that Europeans have done.

00:22:17.360 --> 00:22:22.220
And it's ruled, no joke,
by a group of poet emperors

00:22:22.220 --> 00:22:24.120
and that's nice, you know.

00:22:24.120 --> 00:22:28.230
It's, you know, wouldn't the world
be a better place if it was run

00:22:28.230 --> 00:22:30.970
by poet politicians
or poet philosophers.

00:22:30.970 --> 00:22:37.980 position:56%
So and the striking thing is that
there's sort of a top down approach.

00:22:37.980 --> 00:22:41.750 position:56%
This is often the way China works is
that people, a Chinese person said,

00:22:41.750 --> 00:22:43.050
well, we play follow the leader.

00:22:43.050 --> 00:22:44.350
And I thought really?

00:22:44.350 --> 00:22:47.240
Well, if you think about it
when your emperor's a poet,

00:22:47.240 --> 00:22:48.800
it's going to filter down.

00:22:48.800 --> 00:22:51.730
So there's a tremendous
amount of poetry and writing

00:22:51.730 --> 00:22:56.260
and scientific research going on.

00:22:56.260 --> 00:23:04.150
And it has the characteristic
of all of these places of genius

00:23:04.150 --> 00:23:10.590
and that is that it is
extremely interdisciplinary.

00:23:10.590 --> 00:23:13.480
People are crossing boundaries.

00:23:13.480 --> 00:23:17.430
So I want to share with you just
one section where I'm looking

00:23:17.430 --> 00:23:20.310
at the work of somebody
named Su Dong-Po.

00:23:20.310 --> 00:23:22.630
Now in addition to being a
paint, poet and a painter's,

00:23:22.630 --> 00:23:26.300
Su is much still revered in
Hangzhou by the way was a governor

00:23:26.300 --> 00:23:28.220
and an accomplished engineer.

00:23:28.220 --> 00:23:30.000
His best known project
was a causeway

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:32.800
that traversed West Lake
and still does today.

00:23:32.800 --> 00:23:38.310
Su was a renaissance man 300
years before the Renaissance.

00:23:38.310 --> 00:23:41.820
So as I step out of the small
museum where I'm admiring his work

00:23:41.820 --> 00:23:44.100
to this bright sky in
the city of Hangzhou,

00:23:44.100 --> 00:23:49.390
I find myself wondering why aren't
there more people like that today?

00:23:49.390 --> 00:23:52.110 position:56%
Why must we sequester our ambitions?

00:23:52.110 --> 00:23:54.910
I answer my own question by
imagining what would happen

00:23:54.910 --> 00:23:59.940 position:56%
if a poly-man like Su Dong-Po walked
on to a modern college campus.

00:23:59.940 --> 00:24:02.690
Is it literature you're
interested in, Mr. Su?

00:24:02.690 --> 00:24:05.820
Oh, well, then please see
the School of Humanities.

00:24:05.820 --> 00:24:07.120
Oh, what's that?

00:24:07.120 --> 00:24:08.420
You're a painter?

00:24:08.420 --> 00:24:10.830
Well, please drop by the
Department of Fine Arts.

00:24:10.830 --> 00:24:12.130
I'm sorry.

00:24:12.130 --> 00:24:14.170
It's engineering that
piques your interest?

00:24:14.170 --> 00:24:17.430
Well, we have an excellent
school for that too.

00:24:17.430 --> 00:24:20.150
But I want to do it all, says Su.

00:24:20.150 --> 00:24:22.810
I'm sorry Mr. Su, we
can't help you there.

00:24:22.810 --> 00:24:25.980
Please return when you've
clarified your career objectives.

00:24:25.980 --> 00:24:29.340
Meanwhile if you like I can direct
you to mental health services.

00:24:29.340 --> 00:24:34.620
You see, we don't often question
the rationale for specialization.

00:24:34.620 --> 00:24:38.280
Of course, there was a lot -- there
was less specialization back then,

00:24:38.280 --> 00:24:40.370
a friend told me at a dinner party.

00:24:40.370 --> 00:24:42.880
The world was less complicated.

00:24:42.880 --> 00:24:46.840
It was. But I would argue that
the world was less complicated

00:24:46.840 --> 00:24:49.930
because there was less
specialization.

00:24:49.930 --> 00:24:52.670
A specialist is encouraged,
rewarded,

00:24:52.670 --> 00:24:56.770
for parsing his chosen field
into smaller and smaller morsels,

00:24:56.770 --> 00:24:59.630
then building high walls
around these tiny bits,

00:24:59.630 --> 00:25:02.410
a narrow outlet naturally follows.

00:25:02.410 --> 00:25:05.930
We mourn the death of the
Renaissance man and women.

00:25:05.930 --> 00:25:10.440
Oblivious to the blindingly
obvious fact that we killed him

00:25:10.440 --> 00:25:14.110
and we continue to do so
every day on college campuses

00:25:14.110 --> 00:25:17.410
and in corporate offices
across the land.

00:25:17.410 --> 00:25:21.700
And I think that is one reason why
we are arguably, and it's arguably,

00:25:21.700 --> 00:25:24.610
seeing fewer creative
breakthroughs today.

00:25:24.610 --> 00:25:27.940
Because as I said before the
genius is not a know-it-all;

00:25:27.940 --> 00:25:29.480
the genius is a see-it-all.

00:25:29.480 --> 00:25:31.520
There were physicists
during the time of Einstein

00:25:31.520 --> 00:25:35.160
who knew more physics than
Einstein did, but they weren't able

00:25:35.160 --> 00:25:40.470
to make those connections
that he was able to make.

00:25:40.470 --> 00:25:45.200
And what you see -- let's time
travel a few hundred years past

00:25:45.200 --> 00:25:48.490
Hangzhou to Vienna now of 1900.

00:25:48.490 --> 00:25:51.740
And this -- this was an
incredible flourishing.

00:25:51.740 --> 00:25:55.350
You had the art movement
with Gustav Klimt.

00:25:55.350 --> 00:25:57.440
You had physicists like Ernst Mach.

00:25:57.440 --> 00:25:59.900
You had philosophers.

00:25:59.900 --> 00:26:03.490
You had writers like
Arthur Schnitzler

00:26:03.490 --> 00:26:04.930
and you had Sigmund Freud.

00:26:04.930 --> 00:26:08.210
So what often happens when
you have sparks flying in lots

00:26:08.210 --> 00:26:13.880
of different directions is a
fire of creativity ignites.

00:26:13.880 --> 00:26:18.640
So if you're Sigmund Freud and
you're sitting there in Vienna

00:26:18.640 --> 00:26:21.730
and you see a new art movement,
the Secessionist movement

00:26:21.730 --> 00:26:24.980 position:56%
and you see new developments of the
world of philosophy and mathematics,

00:26:24.980 --> 00:26:29.900 position:56%
you start to think on an unconscious
level that as Freud would put it,

00:26:29.900 --> 00:26:33.340
then why not in my field too.

00:26:33.340 --> 00:26:35.350
Because creativity is contagious.

00:26:35.350 --> 00:26:37.360
There is a contagion effect.

00:26:37.360 --> 00:26:39.710
And that's why I think it's
very important for places

00:26:39.710 --> 00:26:44.170
like Silicon Valley to not
just do technology; right?

00:26:44.170 --> 00:26:47.110
But to have a thriving art
scene there for selfish reasons.

00:26:47.110 --> 00:26:49.730
In addition to art being
beautiful and wonderful, is it --

00:26:49.730 --> 00:26:53.230
actually it's going to
help the technology field

00:26:53.230 --> 00:26:58.660
because these lines we think
are so solid are not, in fact.

00:26:58.660 --> 00:27:02.950
So a couple words about
Silicon Valley

00:27:02.950 --> 00:27:05.350
and then I do want to
take your questions.

00:27:05.350 --> 00:27:08.930 position:56%
It was probably the hardest
chapter for me to write to be honest

00:27:08.930 --> 00:27:11.630
because it's not done yet.

00:27:11.630 --> 00:27:15.570
There's no period at the end of it.

00:27:15.570 --> 00:27:18.460
And people are familiar with it
more than they are with Hangzhou

00:27:18.460 --> 00:27:22.190
so they think they know what
makes Silicon Valley tick.

00:27:22.190 --> 00:27:25.310
I went there with a
completely open mind.

00:27:25.310 --> 00:27:28.860
I did not talk to technology
people because I don't --

00:27:28.860 --> 00:27:32.040
not exclusively because Silicon
Valley actually has very little

00:27:32.040 --> 00:27:34.170
to do with technology.

00:27:34.170 --> 00:27:35.470
I really believe that.

00:27:35.470 --> 00:27:37.430
The product is technology, yes.

00:27:37.430 --> 00:27:40.140
But the process is cultural.

00:27:40.140 --> 00:27:42.090
Right. So I hung out
with anthropologists

00:27:42.090 --> 00:27:44.430
and there are some
anthropologists there who are sort

00:27:44.430 --> 00:27:47.650
of the Margaret Meads of Silicon
Valley who look at the locals

00:27:47.650 --> 00:27:51.300
and their strange customs
and what they do.

00:27:51.300 --> 00:27:57.320 position:56%
And what Silicon Valley is very good
at is it actually resembles a lot

00:27:57.320 --> 00:28:00.300
of these ancient golden
ages in some ways.

00:28:00.300 --> 00:28:04.240
You have that mooching going
on, that borrowing ideas.

00:28:04.240 --> 00:28:07.410
Actually very little,
relatively little is invented

00:28:07.410 --> 00:28:08.710
in Silicon Valley.

00:28:08.710 --> 00:28:12.770
Not the cell phone which was
invested in a suburb of Chicago.

00:28:12.770 --> 00:28:16.240
Not venture capital
which came from New York.

00:28:16.240 --> 00:28:23.050
But there is a system in Silicon
Valley for let's just say for --

00:28:23.050 --> 00:28:26.340
what's the hot word these
days, curating these ideas.

00:28:26.340 --> 00:28:30.870
So as much as places of genius
are magnets for good ideas,

00:28:30.870 --> 00:28:33.370
they also need to be
colanders to sift

00:28:33.370 --> 00:28:35.840
out the good from the bad; right?

00:28:35.840 --> 00:28:40.260
So Jonas Salk two time Nobel prize
winner, no slouch, was once asked

00:28:40.260 --> 00:28:42.620
by a young student, you know,
Dr. Salk, how do you come

00:28:42.620 --> 00:28:44.890
up with so many good ideas?

00:28:44.890 --> 00:28:46.190
He said, well, it's easy.

00:28:46.190 --> 00:28:50.020
I come up lots of ideas and I
throw away the bad ones; right?

00:28:50.020 --> 00:28:53.570
That element of discernment
is hugely important

00:28:53.570 --> 00:28:54.870
and often overlooked.

