So but seriously I was very --

00:42:00.750 --> 00:42:03.600
I felt very bad that I was
not able to include that.

00:42:03.600 --> 00:42:09.290
I had toyed with including a
chapter on Paris of the 1920s.

00:42:09.290 --> 00:42:12.130
But Woody Allen's movie, Midnight
in Paris, had just come out.

00:42:12.130 --> 00:42:14.170
I thought it was overly familiar.

00:42:14.170 --> 00:42:16.010
But I came to regret that decision.

00:42:16.010 --> 00:42:17.310
True story.

00:42:17.310 --> 00:42:19.030
I get a call from -- because
the book's been translated

00:42:19.030 --> 00:42:21.420
into some 16 languages
but not French.

00:42:21.420 --> 00:42:24.350
And I got a call from the French
publisher says Mr. Weiner,

00:42:24.350 --> 00:42:25.650
we like your book.

00:42:25.650 --> 00:42:26.950
It's very nice.

00:42:26.950 --> 00:42:28.250
We would like to publish
it here in France

00:42:28.250 --> 00:42:31.960
but why you don't have a
chapter on the French geniuses.

00:42:31.960 --> 00:42:34.920
We have so many.

00:42:34.920 --> 00:42:36.220
That stung.

00:42:36.220 --> 00:42:39.160
So there a lots of places
I could have included.

00:42:39.160 --> 00:42:41.870
I tried to go with a cross
section geographically,

00:42:41.870 --> 00:42:45.910
temporally across time, and
in terms of familiarity.

00:42:45.910 --> 00:42:47.210
Good question.

00:42:47.210 --> 00:42:48.510
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:42:48.510 --> 00:42:49.810
&gt;&gt; Eric Weiner: Yes?

00:42:49.810 --> 00:42:51.110
&gt;&gt; Hi. This is a rather
trivial question.

00:42:51.110 --> 00:42:52.410
Have you ever --

00:42:52.410 --> 00:42:53.710
&gt;&gt; Eric Weiner: There
are no trivial questions.

00:42:53.710 --> 00:42:55.010
&gt;&gt; Oh, okay.

00:42:55.010 --> 00:42:56.310
Have you ever watched the
series, Silicon Valley?

00:42:56.310 --> 00:42:57.610 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Eric Weiner: Oh, this is trivial.

00:42:57.610 --> 00:43:00.870
&gt;&gt; And if so, -- and if so, do
you have any thoughts about it?

00:43:00.870 --> 00:43:03.000
&gt;&gt; Eric Weiner: I have watched it.

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:07.590
I met one of the guys,
not who stars in it

00:43:07.590 --> 00:43:13.260 position:56%
but who's a venture capitalist named
Roger McNamee who appears in my book

00:43:13.260 --> 00:43:18.630
and who was consulted with -- by
the producers of it, you know.

00:43:18.630 --> 00:43:23.080
And who makes this sort of
cameo appearance in the series.

00:43:23.080 --> 00:43:26.210
And he thought it was spot on.

00:43:26.210 --> 00:43:31.350
And I think it -- it
does a good job of sort

00:43:31.350 --> 00:43:34.570
of puncturing the myth
around it; right?

00:43:34.570 --> 00:43:36.150
And one of those myths is

00:43:36.150 --> 00:43:39.840
that Silicon Valley
embraces failure; right.

00:43:39.840 --> 00:43:41.140
This failure fetish.

00:43:41.140 --> 00:43:43.420
Failure is good, you know.

00:43:43.420 --> 00:43:46.210
In early Silicon Valley,
pioneers said well,

00:43:46.210 --> 00:43:49.710
if you fail in Silicon Valley
out here in the West, you know,

00:43:49.710 --> 00:43:53.670
far away from the East Coast,
your neighbors won't --

00:43:53.670 --> 00:43:56.430
your family won't know and your
neighbors won't care, you know.

00:43:56.430 --> 00:43:57.730
That kind of freedom.

00:43:57.730 --> 00:43:59.210
And there is some truth to that.

00:43:59.210 --> 00:44:02.200
But really if you think about,
if you think about a Steve Jobs

00:44:02.200 --> 00:44:05.400
and his back story, we love
the back story of the failures

00:44:05.400 --> 00:44:08.520
because it ultimately
led to success; right?

00:44:08.520 --> 00:44:12.290
And, in fact, as one
anthropologist points out to me,

00:44:12.290 --> 00:44:14.140
if you fail in Silicon
Valley, you're working

00:44:14.140 --> 00:44:18.400
with a pretty big net, you know,
because you can work again.

00:44:18.400 --> 00:44:20.340
These other places I
looked at if you fail,

00:44:20.340 --> 00:44:22.630
like in renaissance
Florence, you were done.

00:44:22.630 --> 00:44:24.360
You know, the stakes were higher.

00:44:24.360 --> 00:44:27.720
So the show's pretty good,
I think, at, you know,

00:44:27.720 --> 00:44:29.510
it does what all good satire does.

00:44:29.510 --> 00:44:34.650 position:56%
It exaggerates a bit, probably not
as much as we think to make a point.

00:44:34.650 --> 00:44:37.660
And it exaggerates
the culture in order

00:44:37.660 --> 00:44:39.490
to illuminate the culture
of Silicon Valley.

00:44:39.490 --> 00:44:41.040
So yeah and it's funny.

00:44:41.040 --> 00:44:42.520
Don't forget that.

00:44:42.520 --> 00:44:45.720
Not trivial at all.

00:44:45.720 --> 00:44:50.470
&gt;&gt; Hi. I was just wondering if
you had any tips for application

00:44:50.470 --> 00:44:53.780
for those of us who might find
ourselves in jobs that are

00:44:53.780 --> 00:44:56.120
like somewhat bureaucratic
or limited

00:44:56.120 --> 00:44:57.900
by like working within a system.

00:44:57.900 --> 00:45:00.080
Did you find any tips
within your research --

00:45:00.080 --> 00:45:01.380
&gt;&gt; Eric Weiner: Which reminds me,

00:45:01.380 --> 00:45:02.680
I never answered the
government question.

00:45:02.680 --> 00:45:05.990
I'm going to answer that
one and then answer yours.

00:45:05.990 --> 00:45:14.530
I did not include Washington,
D.C. even though I live here.

00:45:14.530 --> 00:45:23.710
I don't think -- this has
probably not been a place of genius

00:45:23.710 --> 00:45:26.020
for a good couple hundred
years to be honest.

00:45:26.020 --> 00:45:32.250
I think because of the caution
that comes with bureaucracy.

00:45:32.250 --> 00:45:36.790
You mentioned being sort of -- if
you're stuck in a bureaucratic job

00:45:36.790 --> 00:45:41.930
or you're stuck somewhere,
you know, bureaucracy

00:45:41.930 --> 00:45:46.000
and creativity are
pretty antithetical

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:49.680
because of the cautiousness.

00:45:49.680 --> 00:45:53.270
There have been certainly --

00:45:53.270 --> 00:45:55.810
well, institutions you can
say that have produced things.

00:45:55.810 --> 00:45:59.050
The Manhattan Project
was a group that was part

00:45:59.050 --> 00:46:01.660
of the federal government,
right, but it was in New Mexico.

00:46:01.660 --> 00:46:03.180
They got them the hell
out of Washington

00:46:03.180 --> 00:46:05.620
and said go to New Mexico.

00:46:05.620 --> 00:46:08.630
And Bell Labs while not
government was a corporation

00:46:08.630 --> 00:46:11.620
that produced lots
of creative places.

00:46:11.620 --> 00:46:16.660
I think what the things you
can do and this is sort of one

00:46:16.660 --> 00:46:19.450
of the points in my
book is that, you know,

00:46:19.450 --> 00:46:23.340
we don't need an ancient
Florence or anything like that.

00:46:23.340 --> 00:46:25.830
But the thing -- there
are lessons --

00:46:25.830 --> 00:46:28.570
this is [inaudible]
with things you can use

00:46:28.570 --> 00:46:30.180
to be less miserable in your job.

00:46:30.180 --> 00:46:33.100
One, is you can go for a walk.

00:46:33.100 --> 00:46:34.400
Can you get out of your office?

00:46:34.400 --> 00:46:36.100
If you can that's good, okay.

00:46:36.100 --> 00:46:37.840
Because lots of geniuses
have walked.

00:46:37.840 --> 00:46:40.770
Beethoven was a walker, Freud was a
walker, other people were walkers.

00:46:40.770 --> 00:46:45.060 position:56%
There's something about walking
that's very conducive to creativity.

00:46:45.060 --> 00:46:47.380
Go to a coffee shop if you can.

00:46:47.380 --> 00:46:50.740
Because there's the
ideal decibel level,

00:46:50.740 --> 00:46:53.100
research shows, for
creative thinking.

00:46:53.100 --> 00:46:56.840
It's not complete silence and
it's not really loud noises.

00:46:56.840 --> 00:46:59.450
It's about 70 decibels,
that background din.

00:46:59.450 --> 00:47:01.220
I'm convinced this
is one of the keys

00:47:01.220 --> 00:47:05.300
to Starbucks success,
that background din.

00:47:05.300 --> 00:47:12.600
And also you can engage in some
creative thinking exercises,

00:47:12.600 --> 00:47:17.320
you know, such as what's
called homeopathic thinking,

00:47:17.320 --> 00:47:19.030
taking two contradictory ideas

00:47:19.030 --> 00:47:21.780
and juxtaposing them
and things like that.

00:47:21.780 --> 00:47:23.770
But I would caution you and
this is sort of the whole point

00:47:23.770 --> 00:47:27.250
of my book is that I think a lot of
this creativity training that goes

00:47:27.250 --> 00:47:31.910
on in corporations and institutions
is not that helpful if the people

00:47:31.910 --> 00:47:35.910
at the top are not open
to these new ideas.

00:47:35.910 --> 00:47:37.420
You need someone at
the top who's going

00:47:37.420 --> 00:47:39.180
to say yes, let's run with that.

00:47:39.180 --> 00:47:41.440
Otherwise, you can have all
the creative thinking exercises

00:47:41.440 --> 00:47:43.290
in the world and you're
just going to have a lot

00:47:43.290 --> 00:47:45.810
of frustrated creative employees.

00:47:45.810 --> 00:47:48.310
And on that kind of downer
of a note, I'm going to have

00:47:48.310 --> 00:47:50.510
to say thank you very much.

00:47:50.510 --> 00:47:55.190
[ Applause ]

